#let images = (
  "17-1": (
    caption: [The organs of the urinary system. The urinary system showing kidneys, ureters, urinary bladder, and urethra. The kidneys receive blood from the renal arteries and return it via renal veins. Urine flows from the kidneys through ureters to the bladder for storage.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-2": (
    caption: [The structure of a kidney. (a) A coronal section showing renal cortex, renal medulla, renal pyramids, renal pelvis, calyces, and major blood vessels. (b) A magnified view of a renal pyramid showing the position of nephrons. (c) A single nephron tubule showing glomerular capsule, proximal convoluted tubule, loop of Henle, distal convoluted tubule, and collecting duct.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-3": (
    caption: [A pseudocolor radiograph of the urinary system. The calyces of the kidneys, renal pelvises, ureters, and urinary bladder are visible in this imaging study, showing the path of urine flow through the urinary system.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-4": (
    caption: [Major blood vessels of the kidney. Illustration showing renal artery, interlobar arteries and veins, arcuate arteries and veins, and interlobular arteries and veins that carry blood into the renal medulla and cortex. These vessels form the vascular supply essential for kidney function.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-5": (
    caption: [The nephron tubules and associated blood vessels. Blood flow from glomerulus to efferent arteriole, to peritubular capillaries, and to venous drainage. The nephron regions include glomerular capsule, proximal convoluted tubule, loop of Henle (descending and ascending limbs), distal convoluted tubule, and collecting duct.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-6": (
    caption: [The contents of a renal pyramid. (a) The position of cortical and juxtamedullary nephrons within the renal pyramid. Cortical nephrons have short loops of Henle in the outer medulla, while juxtamedullary nephrons have long loops extending deep into the inner medulla. (b) Direction of blood flow in the vessels indicated with arrows.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-7": (
    caption: [A scanning electron micrograph of the glomerular capillaries and capsule. The inner (visceral) layer of the glomerular (Bowman's) capsule is composed of podocytes with very fine extensions forming foot processes (pedicels) that interdigitate around the glomerular capillaries. Spaces between adjacent foot processes form filtration slits.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-8": (
    caption: [The structure of the glomerulus and capsule. The relationship between glomerular capillaries and the inner layer of the glomerular (Bowman's) capsule. Filtered molecules pass out of the fenestrae of the capillaries, through the basement membrane and filtration slits, to enter the cavity of the capsule.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-9": (
    caption: [An electron micrograph of the filtration barrier. The barrier separating the capillary lumen from the cavity of the glomerular (Bowman's) capsule consists of capillary endothelium with fenestrae, basement membrane, and slit diaphragms between podocyte foot processes. This three-layered barrier allows selective filtration.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-10": (
    caption: [The formation of glomerular ultrafiltrate. Only a very small proportion of plasma proteins (large molecules) are filtered, but smaller plasma solutes easily enter the glomerular ultrafiltrate. Arrows indicate the direction of filtration from capillaries into the capsule space. The ultrafiltrate composition differs from plasma mainly in its low protein content.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-11": (
    caption: [Sympathetic nerve effects on kidney function. Increased sympathetic nerve activity causes vasoconstriction of afferent arterioles, reducing glomerular filtration rate (GFR), and stimulates renin secretion from juxtaglomerular cells. This affects blood pressure regulation and fluid balance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-12": (
    caption: [Filtration and reabsorption. Plasma water and dissolved solutes (except proteins) enter the glomerular ultrafiltrate by filtration, but most filtered molecules are reabsorbed. Reabsorption refers to transport of molecules from tubular filtrate back into the blood through peritubular capillaries.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-13": (
    caption: [Salt and water reabsorption in the proximal tubule. Sodium is actively transported out of the filtrate and chloride follows passively by electrical attraction. Water follows the salt out of the tubular filtrate into the peritubular capillaries by osmosis. About 65% of filtered water and salt is reabsorbed here.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-14": (
    caption: [The countercurrent multiplier system. (1) Extrusion of sodium chloride from the ascending limb makes the surrounding interstitial fluid more concentrated. (2) The descending limb is passively permeable to water, causing its fluid to increase in concentration as water leaves. (3) This creates a concentration gradient in the medulla essential for water reabsorption.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-15": (
    caption: [The transport of ions in the ascending limb. (1) In the thick segment, Na+ and K+ together with two Cl– enter tubule cells via the Na-K-2Cl cotransporter. (2) Na+ is actively transported out by Na+/K+-ATPase pumps and Cl– follows passively. (3) K+ diffuses back into the tubular fluid, making it electrically positive and driving paracellular reabsorption.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-16": (
    caption: [Countercurrent exchange in the vasa recta. The diffusion of salt and water first into and then out of these blood vessels helps maintain the hypertonicity of the interstitial fluid in the renal medulla. Numbers indicate osmolality (mOsm) at different levels, showing the preservation of the medullary concentration gradient.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-17": (
    caption: [The role of urea in urine concentration. (1) Urea diffuses out of the inner collecting duct in the renal medulla into the interstitial fluid. (2) It can pass into the ascending limb of the loop of Henle, recycling in the interstitial fluid. This urea recycling contributes significantly to the hypertonicity of the medullary interstitium.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-18": (
    caption: [The osmolality of different regions of the kidney. The countercurrent multiplier system in the loop of Henle and countercurrent exchange in the vasa recta create a hypertonic renal medulla. Under antidiuretic hormone (ADH) influence, the collecting duct becomes more permeable to water, allowing water reabsorption and urine concentration.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-19": (
    caption: [ADH stimulation of aquaporin channels. (a) When ADH is absent, aquaporin-2 channels are located in intracellular vesicle membranes within collecting duct cells. (b-c) ADH binding triggers vesicle fusion with the plasma membrane and insertion of aquaporin channels. (d) When ADH is withdrawn, aquaporins are retrieved by endocytosis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-20": (
    caption: [Homeostasis of plasma concentration maintained by ADH. In dehydration, increased ADH secretion reduces water excretion in urine, conserving body water. In overhydration, decreased ADH secretion allows excess water elimination. Negative feedback mechanisms involving osmoreceptors regulate ADH secretion to maintain plasma osmolality.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-21": (
    caption: [Secretion is the reverse of reabsorption. Secretion refers to active transport of substances from peritubular capillaries into the tubular fluid, opposite to reabsorption. Both processes occur across tubule walls and involve carrier-mediated transport mechanisms for various substances including drugs and metabolic wastes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-22": (
    caption: [The renal clearance of inulin. (a) Glomerular blood with dissolved inulin is filtered. (b) All filtered inulin enters the urine while most filtered water is reabsorbed. (c) Blood leaving the kidneys in the renal vein contains less inulin than arterial blood. Inulin clearance equals GFR because inulin is freely filtered but neither reabsorbed nor secreted.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-23": (
    caption: [The renal clearance of PAH (para-aminohippuric acid). (a) PAH in glomerular blood (b) is filtered into glomerular capsules and (c) the remainder is secreted from peritubular capillaries into nephron tubules, so all blood leaving the kidneys is free of PAH. PAH clearance equals total renal blood flow.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-24": (
    caption: [The mechanism of reabsorption in the proximal tubule. Molecules reabsorbed pass through tubule cells from the apical membrane (facing filtrate) to the basolateral membrane (facing blood). (1) Coupled transport of Na+ with glucose or amino acids at apical membrane. (2) Na+/K+-ATPase pumps in basolateral membrane actively transport Na+ into interstitial fluid. (3) Glucose and amino acids diffuse out via facilitated diffusion.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-25": (
    caption: [Potassium is reabsorbed and secreted. K+ is almost completely reabsorbed in the proximal tubule, but under aldosterone stimulation, it is secreted into the cortical collecting duct. All K+ in urine derives from secretion rather than filtration. This allows regulation of plasma K+ levels independently of sodium balance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-26": (
    caption: [The juxtaglomerular apparatus. (a) The region of contact between the afferent arteriole and the last portion of the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle. (b) Afferent arterioles contain granular cells that secrete renin. Tubule cells in contact with granular cells form the macula densa, which senses tubular fluid composition and regulates renin secretion.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-27": (
    caption: [Homeostasis of plasma Na+. The sequence of events by which low sodium intake leads to increased sodium reabsorption by the kidneys through the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. Decreased blood volume/pressure triggers renin secretion, leading to angiotensin II formation and aldosterone release, which increases Na+ reabsorption. Negative feedback loop shown with dashed arrow.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-28": (
    caption: [Secretion of K+ and H+. In the distal tubule, K+ and H+ are secreted in response to the potential difference produced by Na+ reabsorption. High concentrations of H+ may decrease K+ secretion and vice versa, showing competition between these ions for secretion mechanisms.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-29": (
    caption: [Acidification of the urine. The process by which urine becomes acidified and bicarbonate is reabsorbed from the filtrate. H+ secretion into tubular fluid is coupled with bicarbonate reabsorption into blood. Carbonic anhydrase (CA) in tubule cells catalyzes formation of H2CO3. Phosphate and ammonia buffers in urine prevent excessive pH drop.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "17-30": (
    caption: [Sites of action of clinical diuretics. Different diuretic drugs act at various nephron sites to inhibit water reabsorption. Loop diuretics act on the ascending limb of Henle, thiazides on the distal tubule, and K+-sparing diuretics on the collecting duct. These actions lower blood volume and pressure by increasing urine output.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-1": (
    caption: [Regulation of the glomerular filtration rate (GFR). Summary of sympathetic nerve effects, autoregulation mechanisms, and hormonal regulation affecting GFR through changes in afferent and efferent arteriole diameter and glomerular capillary pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-2": (
    caption: [Transport properties of different segments of the renal tubules and collecting ducts. Comparison of active and passive transport mechanisms for Na+, water, urea, and other substances in the proximal tubule, loop of Henle (descending and ascending limbs), distal tubule, and collecting duct.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-3": (
    caption: [Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) secretion and action. Stimuli for ADH release (increased plasma osmolality, decreased blood volume/pressure), mechanisms of action (aquaporin-2 insertion), and effects on water reabsorption and urine concentration. Also covers diabetes insipidus causes and treatment.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-4": (
    caption: [Effects of filtration, reabsorption, and secretion on renal plasma clearance. How these three processes affect clearance rates relative to inulin clearance (which equals GFR). Substances only filtered have clearance equal to inulin; reabsorption decreases clearance; secretion increases clearance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-5": (
    caption: [Renal handling of different plasma molecules. Summary showing how kidneys process glucose, amino acids, urea, creatinine, PAH, and other substances through filtration, reabsorption, and/or secretion. Includes normal plasma concentrations and clinical significance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-6": (
    caption: [Regulation of renin and aldosterone secretion. Factors stimulating and inhibiting renin release from juxtaglomerular cells (decreased blood pressure, sympathetic stimulation, low Na+ at macula densa) and subsequent aldosterone secretion from adrenal cortex. Effects on Na+ and K+ balance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-7": (
    caption: [Categories of disturbances in acid-base balance. Classification of metabolic and respiratory acidosis and alkalosis, including causes (e.g., ketoacidosis, hyperventilation), compensatory mechanisms, and changes in blood pH, PCO2, and bicarbonate concentration.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-17-8": (
    caption: [Actions of different classes of diuretics. Mechanisms and sites of action for loop diuretics (furosemide), thiazides, carbonic anhydrase inhibitors, and potassium-sparing diuretics (spironolactone, amiloride). Effects on Na+, K+, and water excretion, and clinical applications.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
